subSubSection.paragraph:
Abdomen
. Abdominal tergite VII gently emarginate at posterior margin; tergite VIII (
Fig. 2A
) subhexagonal, gently emarginate at posterior margin, apical 1/8 of dorsal surface and apical 2/3 of lateral margins with long setae. Abdominal ventrites without coarse punctures; ventrite VII gently emarginate at posterior margin; ventrite VIII (
Fig. 2B
) with apical sclerotized area transversely oblong, substraight at posterior margin; spiculum relictum (
Figs. 2A–C
) slender, about 3.5 times as long as apical area. Spiculum gastrale (
Figs. 2D–F
) with stem 2.2 times longer than branches; stem gently curved in lateral view (
Fig. 2F
).

Male genitalia
. Tegmen (
Figs. 3A–B
) widest at middle, moderately curved ventrally in lateral view (
Fig. 3C
); parameres 2/7 length of tegmen, distinctly elongate, gradually convergent towards round apices, each apex with short setae of various lengths and long ones near apices (
Fig. 3D
); tegminal struts of connected basally. Median lobe (
Figs. 3E–F
) shorter than tegmen, distinctly curved ventrally in lateral view (
Fig. 3G
); dorsal plate (
Fig. 3H
) truncated at apex; ventral plate (
Fig. 3H
) longer than dorsal plate, spatulate at apical margin; basal struts (
Figs. 3E–F
) half length of median lobe.
